Jeopardy Analysis

Elizabeth Wickes

October 27, 2014

Data description

Collection and preparation

A total of 7961 players were imported, representing the subset of players who were detected to be from the United States, with all duplicates removed. Duplicates were defined as entities with matching name and winnings values.

Data were pulled from player statistics HTML pages from J-Archive!. Example page:
http://j-archive.com/showplayerstats.php?player_id=8000.

Players were scraped and associated data was gathered. Occupational statements were aligned to the 2010 SOC code system. Some additional SOC codes and groups were added to improve this matching. 28% of the players occupational statements failed to match a controlled SOC code. The curated version of the SOC code system is available here.

All code to produce the associated CSV files is located in an IPython Notebook available for viewing and download here. All original player and analysis files are available within this github repository.

The data have been split to only include players participating in 2003 and after, due to a rules change that removed the limit on the number of games in which each champion may compete. The frequencies of players participating in numbers of games are charted below.

Exploring the impact of Ken Jennings

The majority of plots and other descriptives involving winnings utilize a dataset that excludes Ken Jennings. Ken is the highest winning player ever on Jeopardy!, with a total of $3,162,085.00. The standard deviation for the set of players after 2003 with Ken is $60,874.44 and is $38,146.19 when Ken is removed. His winnings have a z-score of 51.574 when compared to the data set including his value, and 82.3215 when excluding him. This z-score goes down to 29.8769 when looking just within the subset of players who have participated in more than one game.

Data Mean SD
2003 and after, all players $22,549.61 $60,874.44
2003 and after, excluding Ken $21,832.82 $38,146.19

The distribution of winnings is highly skewed to the right and lacks a normal distribution. The distribution of winnings for players participating in just one game, indicating that they played without winning, is less skewed, but still not normal. The data below include Ken Jennings.
